Amazing food and experience. Social distancing guidelines were kept strictly, and I felt very safe and comfortable during my stay. Our server was Luigi, and I can't stress enough how great his service was. Super nice and funny and very personable. The burrata was divine. By itself, it's a very silky mouthfeel, and when topped with the honey and truffles, it unleashes the inner sweetness of the cheese. The bed of greens it lied on was the perfect earthy flavor to ground it and make sure it didn't become a cloying taste instead. I love it. We were also recommended dishes with porcini mushrooms since they are currently in season, and I was glad. The risotto I had was delicious. And of course, the tiramisu of Al Tiramisu is the smooth, creamy, perfect finish to the night.

Authentic Italian restaurant with al dente pasta tucked in a cozy row home. My hubby and I dropped $200 on a wonderful dinner and it was well worth every penny! The Papperdelle mushroom pasta, chestnut soup, housemade limoncello, and Chianti were the highlights.  The complementary fluffy focaccia and rustic bread were tasty and served with olive oil and tapenade. Off to a good start!  Chianti (5/5) - Enjoyed a couple of glasses of Chianti over the bread and pasta. Perfect pairing of food with wine!  Zuppa del giorno Soup of the day (5/5) - The Chestnut Soup was creamy and bursting with flavor. Glad I ordered it! The bread was perfect for mopping up the soup. Worth ordering and saving room for.  Scamorza affumicata gratinata su crosta di pane con acciughe (2/5)- Bread smothered with cheese. Fun to try, but very rich and cheesy! I would save your appetite for the soup and main course.  Pappardelle Strappate Su Ragu Di Funghi (5/5) - The wide noocdles were cooked al dente loaded with tasty mushrooms.  Ravioli Di Caciocavallo Podolico E Foglie Di Bietola in Burro E Salvia (4/5) - Ravioli stuffed with burrata in butter sage sauce is a simple dish which my hubby thoroughly enjoyed, while I preferred the Papperdelle.  Sfalde Di Salmone Con Salsa All'arancia (5/5) - My hubby enjoyed the fresh fish.  Tiramisu (3/5) - Doesn't quite live up to the restaurant name. It was a bit dry and could use more liquor to make the dessert more moist and less dense.  Limoncello (5/5) - The house-made limoncello was a hidden gem, tasty and potent! Fun way to end a meal.  Highly recommend! Off the beaten path on P street, worth trekking over for a great culinary experience!

Great food and friendly staff who know a lot about the cuisine.  I had a great time on New Year's Eve and they were really nice about accommodating an error with my reservation.  Luigi even gave my date a rose on the way out!

One of the best Italian restaurant in this location.Mostly i visit it.They provide wonderful services to their customers.Food was yummy and fresh. Staff was very honest and great.amazing place, neat and clean. Must recommended.

Very nice ambience and service, especially for a date. Our entrées in particular were nothing special (both pasta), and the almond chocolate cake was also underwhelming for dessert. They bring around a tray of fresh fish to each table to show off the day’s catch (served grilled), so maybe next time I’ll give that a try instead. Barata appetizer was good.
Great service, food and drinks. Terrific time, I'd come back in a heartbeat.

Not the nicest interior but very homey like you're entering someone's basement to have dinner.   You are served focaccia and table bread accompanied by an olive tapenade.  APPETIZER: Burrata del Salento con miele e tartufo nero $18 burrata from Salento / local honey / black truffle bits *I was hoping the burrata would be really creamy and have lots of truffle flavor but the whole dish fell flat and definitely didn't have the creaminess of a burrata and barely any truffle flavor.  The slaw that came underneath didn't really add anything to the dish.  ENTREES: Maine Lobster Linguine *This was the best thing I ate and it was because of the lobster not the pasta.  The linguine tasted like box pasta, it didn't taste homemade, I'm not sure if their pasta is homemade.  The lobster was cooked perfectly and the tomato sauce was very simple and didn't overwhelm the lobster.  This menu item is usually listed on their daily specials and I would recommend trying this dish especially if you're a lobster fan.  You also have the option to do risotto instead of linguine.  Spinach & 4 Cheese Ravioli *Mostly pasta barely any filling, it was like sad deflated raviolis pretty disappointing.  You'll still be very hungry after eating this.  DESSERT: Tartufo al cioccolato Frozen zabaglione covered in chocolate gelato, hazelnuts and cocoa *this was pretty tasty reminds me of an ice cream version of the ferrero rocher chocolate. *I also opted not to the get the tiramisu because so many Yelpers mentioned it was small and mediocre.  SERVICE: Consistent throughout dinner no complaints here, water and wine glasses were always full.  The server verbally went through the daily specials, I wish they had them printed out just because there were so many to listen to and remember.

The extra cost would have been fine IF the food had been excellent which was not the case for the fish or the chicken. They were adequate but not to the degree expected. Our children did like the duck which was prepared well.

I dined on marinated Portobello mushrooms with goat cheese,  ravioli with truffles, delicately grilled whole Popano, and closed with the signature tiramisu and house crafted sambuca.  Each element stands on its own merits and was a joy to savior.  All of this pared with impeccable service made for a wonderful evening.

Very charming place with great food, I'd say this is a four course Italian restaurant, great for a romantic occasion. Staff is very friendly and food is very good. Just pay attention and ask for the price of the specials that that they offer, it can be much more expensive than the regular options available on the menu. Three complaints: (1) The portions are small. (2) When I ordered hot tea with lemon and honey, the tea arrived without lemon or honey, I had to ask again to receive honey. (3) Where we were seated we couldn't see or feel the fireplace, but to be fair I didn't ask to be seated near it.  If these sound like nitpicks, they are. The food was delicious, the ambience and service excellent. These minor complaints were not enough to dock a star, and I'd gladly eat here again.

I have eaten here many times, the food is always superb, the ambience is quiet and cozy. My complaint is the waitstaff, they are attentive but always trying to rush you out the door. Tonight was no exception. It was a special night for us as I was proposing to my girlfriend. My server, Luis, brought the main dishes out with the first dish, our pasta. The main dishes on the menu are clearly marked Secondi. When I questioned why he did this he said because we we're splitting our pasta dish. Ridiculous. So our main dish sat in the middle of the table getting cold while we ate our pasta. Out of his greed and selfishness he spoiled our special night.

This resturaunt rushed us in and out in 35 minutes for a $140 for 2 meal. Steak was no better than an olive garden steak but double the price. 9 tiny tortellini for $25. The salads were $15 and were basically just lettuce. The following night...I ate at a place up the street La Tomatoe and it was the exact opposite....please eat there instead.

The servers were initially trying to be helpful, but otherwise seemed really inexperienced. The food was brought out way too quickly for it to have been made in that time, and prepared, heated food at this price is unacceptable. But the train wreck didn't stop there as the dish we were served with was literally tasteless. The bland food made me thankful for the fact that the portion sizes were laughably small. Obviously, our complaints have been made to the servers, but they didn't really seem to understand them. No compensation was offered on our bill either. They did offer desserts, although it wasn't made clear whether those were supposed to be the compensation, but it didn't matter, as after all of this, we had no intentions of staying there any longer.

Recently visited Al Tiramisu with my wife and son. We were in the neighbourhood for spring break and it was walking distance from our hotel. Tried it after the initial place were headed was booked solid with hours of waiting time. Immediately we were greeted at the door by 2 very friendly people and even though we didn't have a reservation, it wasn't a problem.  The food was amazing, (lobster linguine and blazed duck breast), with many specials for the evening off the menu as well. Service was equally amazing as they constantly checked in on us, had pleasant conversation and even spoke to our young son in a kind manor (even when he was acting his age once in a while). Al Tiramisu was a very pleasant surprise and I would completely recommend it to anyone who might have a chance to visit.
Amazing food and service!

Nice comfortable little place.  They certainly cram too many tables in the space so you are elbow to elbow with the table next to you.  Made reservations but still was seated in the front by the door when it was 20 degrees out.  The lobster bisque was amazing but the short ribs fell a bit short on flavor and meat quality.  Small but good wine list.

Authentic Italian dishes, with a great staff. The pasta is made in house, and they show you the whole fish when they tell you the specials so you know exactly what you're getting. Always enjoy going here.

Service was the worst! I work as a concierge in a hotel, I recommend this place to plenty of people per day. I decided to go and try it. When I got the bill I asked the server if they offered any discount for concierges. He said do you have a business card and I told him only managers have cards at my property and I'm a concierge and I don't have one, but he can call my property and confirm. He kind of embarrassed me infront of my friend saying you could be anyone and didn't want to do any further thing for me. He should have responded in another way maybe saying unfortunately we don't have any discounts for anyone or another appropriate way. This happened like seven month ago and the server said he was also a manager. Never after that day I have recomended this place to anyone.
Really bad food - it was precooked and heated up poorly. Stay away!

Last night, we celebrated our second anniversary there because of the good reviews we read about it, including all the celebrities who visited it; BUT, the service wasn’t that great, we could hardly talk and my wife got food poison.  I had the lobster risotto and it was very tasteful; however, the Polpo del mediterraneo grigliato seems to have pretty bad origins.  I would think twice now to recommend it.
Excellent and knowledgeable servers. The ravioli and gnocchi are both great, I haven't had anything else.
Great Italian dining near Embassy Row

Amazing and authentic Italian. While on a trip to DC with the family, we found this intimate spot near the hotel. Walked I without a reservation and was blown away. I had handmade parpadelle with a delicious mushroom ragu. O_o

Four for early dinner.Cozy,empty and attentive service.0rdered a 90 dollar wine and was charged 160.One of the specials was veal roast. Two of us ordered the veal....do not neglect To ask price of specials.....price will not be mentioned by the server. The veal was rolled into a wheel shape and served with a sauce. The offering was so thin you could read thro it.Half was fat and it was so over done it was a struggle to cut. The waiter asked how we liked our dinner and I told him it was grossly over cooked. He then asked if he could replace it with something else.....kudos to the waiter, but we declined. Called when I got home and spoke to the waiter about over charge on the WINE which was immediately corrected. This place came highly recommended for its food. 2 risottos,i salad,1 wine,1 duck 2 veal 300.00. Quality of food....DON'T GO.

We were well-received for an early dinner; and initial service fine. Restaurant is rather small, and narrow; acoustics very poor and make it almost impossible to have a conversation. Upon ordering, appetizers arrived literally within a minute; obviously not freshly made but were fairly good, better than adequate. 1 of 3 dinners brought to table was wrong meal; waiter insisted it was what had been ordered, but because I do not ever eat what was served, no question and I told him to take it back. Waiter agreed to have the correct meal (red snapper) prepared, but after a long wait and after others in the party were through with their meals, and only after I told the waiter to bring the meal or cancel it, it was brought to the table (on an extremely hot plate!) It was at best a mediocre, and extremely small portion of red snapper. Then a large party was seated closely behind our table, and additional chairs brought to that table which necessitated my moving where I was seated. And finally, despite our very unpleasant meal, no accommodation was made or offered on the bill. I do not mind paying $400 for a $400 meal (for 3).  This was not worth it; not even close. This restaurant claims to cater to the rich and famous. They can have it!
This is one of Washington's hidden treasures.  The food is always outstanding.   Luigi, Nadija and the entire crew make every guest feel that they are the most important person in the restaurant.

I was disappointed - at first, the service was good, and the waiters (I think I had David) were well informed about the menu and the ingredients.   Later, I ordered pasta with clams, and ended up getting sick and throwing up a bad clam in the men's room.   I mistakenly thought that they would comp the dish.  They didn't.   I won't return.

No extravagent decoration. No over the top fancy dishes. Just delicious food, knowledgeable waitstaff with attentive service. A solid 4 star in my book. For appetizers, we had the seared scallop with squid ink infused cannelini bean purée and grilled baby octopus, both were tasty with the right amount of tenderness. For entrees, we had the lobster risotto and mushroom ragu pasta. Both were delicious but the lobster risotto especially stood out. The lobster was poached to perfection and not overcooked as in many pasta dishes. The portions were big and we were stuffed at the end. We couldn't pass on the tiramisu for dessert as that's what the restaurant was seemingly named after. However it was not memorable. But overall it was a great experience and I'd return to try their other dishes.
Terrific, small intimate place with attentive wait staff, fresh ingredients and great meals. All in our party loved it.
Overrated on the food but the decor could get higher number. Lets say food was 22, and the decor was 23. Really professional and helpful waiter.
Excellent food - cannot do better. Service is wonderful - expensive and worth every penny. Fine wine list and recommendations. Everyone should try at least once.
I love this place. The specials are the chef's fancy, and always turn out wonderfully. If you get the butternut squash ravioli from here, you'll be in heaven.
The Osso Bucco is the best in DC!  The wines are perfect for the food offerings and the staff is lively.  A great experience to be had.
Fine classic Italian, everything was spot-on except the over-dressed fennel salad.  But the mozarella was fresh, the fish was perfect, and the eponymous dessert is a winner.
consistently very good food, wine and service. comfortable atmosphere.
